This paper deals with bibliometric analysis, which is a subfield of computer science that focuses on the quantitative analysis of scientific publications. The paper specifically compares bibliometric statistics obtained from two major databases, Web of Science and Scopus, which are commonly used in the field of computer science. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DL (Digital Libraries), which deals with the organization, retrieval, and dissemination of digital information. Other likely sub-categories include cs.IR (Information Retrieval), which deals with the retrieval of information from large collections of data, cs.CY (Computers and Society), which deals with the social and ethical implications of computing, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which deals with the analysis of social and information networks, and cs.LG (Machine Learning), which deals with the development of algorithms that can learn from data.
